        <h2>7 TASK SPECIFIC METHODOLOGY</h2>

        <h3>BIOFOULING REMOVAL</h3>
        <p>All biofouling on the {{scopeAreasText}} will be removed using dive hand tools {{#if captureRequired}}with capture and filtration{{else}}appropriate to the fouling level{{/if}}. The treatment process must avoid damaging anti-fouling coatings wherever possible and comply with containment and waste capture protocols outlined in the 2025 IWHC Exposure Draft.</p>
        <p>Helmet-mounted CCTV will be used to record all cleaning activities, with footage retained as part of job documentation. This video will serve two primary purposes: to measure the capture standard and to verify visual compliance by showing whether any visible debris escapes the system.</p>
        {{#if captureRequired}}
        <p>Cleaning methods will utilise vacuum heads with removable scraper blades, with waste filtered through a 10-micron unit. The Dive Supervisor will assess each method's effectiveness in real-time and consult Franmarine Operations Management before implementing alternative methods. If switching cleaning heads, each head type must be tested individually, and the changeover documented as per IWHC assessment protocols. This approach supports reactive management strategies for unacceptable discharge.</p>
        {{/if}}
        <p>Should IMS be detected during operations, DPIRD will be notified immediately, and further works will be conducted under their discretion and authority.</p>

        <h3>REGULATORY COMPLIANCE</h3>
        <p>The cleaning methodology aligns with the Decision Support Tool outlined in Chapter 8 of the 2025 IWHC draft guidelines and supports the operational standards proposed by regulatory bodies. Real-time video chat (via MarineStream) ensures regulatory oversight during operations is available, satisfying the compliance verification requirements introduced in the latest Exposure Draft.</p>
        <p>{{operatingProfileCompliance}}</p>
        <p>Franmarines in-water cleaning process is agnostic to vessel type and aligns with the standards proposed in the WA regulatory environment. DPIRD is a key stakeholder in marine pest management. As such, all IMS risks must be addressed through inspection, sampling, and reporting.</p>
        <p>All planned operations will conform with Fremantle Port Authority requirements, and approvals are expected to follow formal permit-to-operate processes. Any methodology adjustments or contingency measures implemented during the project must be documented in SAP and made available to regulators for review.</p>

        {{#if sapRequired}}
        <h3>CHEMICAL CONTAMINATION MANAGEMENT</h3>
        <p>To ensure compliance with the chemical contamination standards set by the 2025 IWHC draft guidelines, a comprehensive Sampling Analysis Plan (SAP) has been developed. This SAP governs all sampling and monitoring of discharge during cleaning operations and ensures that effluent does not contain toxicants in concentrations exceeding limits listed in the ANZG 2018 guidelines for marine water quality.</p>
        <p>Sampling will occur at three spatially distinct sites (e.g. above, below, and downstream of the cleaning head), with testing repeated over three occasions during cleaning operations. A control site and an ambient location will also be included to provide baseline comparisons. The SAP includes analyte testing for TSS, biocides, copper, and zinc, as well as QA/QC procedures. All sample rationale must be documented and traceable.</p>
        <p>Sampling containers will be prepared and deployed by trained personnel in line with pre-approved procedures. Data will be assessed for statistical variation using appropriate methods (e.g. ANOVA), ensuring sufficient replication and compliance with exposure thresholds.</p>
        <p>Franmarine will provide vessel-specific operational information to FPA and other regulators to support pre-approval processes. The SAP includes reactive measures if live fauna or unacceptable chemical levels are detected and outlines the steps to notify regulators and repeat viability testing where applicable.</p>
        {{/if}}
    </section>

